### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

forms

### Description

To my best understanding the only way to print an error message in the HTML template is to pass a number as the index of array returned by [errors()](https://angular.dev/api/forms/signals/FieldState#errors) method:

HTML:
```
@if (loginForm.email().invalid() && loginForm.email().dirty()) {
    <div>{{ loginForm.email().errors()[0].message }}</div>
    <div>{{ loginForm.email().errors()[1].message }}</div>
}
```

TS:
```
loginForm = form(this.userFields, (path: SchemaPathTree<ILoginFields, PathKind.Root>) => {
    required(path.email, { message: 'Email is required' });
    pattern(path.email, /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/, { message: 'Invalid email format' });
});
```

Would it be possible to add something similar to [hasError](https://angular.dev/api/forms/FormControl#hasError) method from FormControl so that the error messages would not be accessed via "magic numbers"?

### Proposed solution

```
@if (loginForm.email().invalid() && loginForm.email().dirty()) {
  <div class="alert">
    @if (loginForm.email().hasError('required')) {
      <div class="form-error">E-mail is required.</div>
    }
    @if (loginForm.email().hasError('pattern')) {
      <div class="form-error form-error--secondary">Please provide a valid-email address.</div>
    }
  </div>
}
```

### Alternatives considered

```
@if (loginForm.email().invalid() && loginForm.email().dirty()) {
  <div class="alert">
    @if (loginForm.email().errors().required) {
      <div class="form-error">E-mail is required.</div>
    }
    @if (loginForm.email().errors().pattern) {
      <div class="form-error form-error--secondary">Please provide a valid-email address.</div>
    }
  </div>
}
```

